			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Hyperthreading means the single CPU can pretend to be two CPUs and get marginally better use out of it's processing units.  On applications designed to use multiple CPUs you can get a 10-30% increase in speed.  Most games aren't built to deal well with this though so don't expect much more than 10% performance improvement.
<br />

<br />
You don't need dual channel memory for hyperthreading.  All dual channel memory does is gives you better bandwidth between the north bridge and the RAM.
<br />

<br />
Dd</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
